*Proof of Theorem <a href="#thm.Main1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm.Main1">1</a>.* By the discussion above, it is sufficient to consider the case $\lambda_1<\lambda_2$. Assume that $z$ is a gap boundary, that is, $2\mathop{\mathrm{rot}}(\Phi,S^{{\sharp}}_z)=k\Phi$ for some $k\in \mathbb{Z}$. Then, by Theorem <a href="#thm:ARC" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:ARC">10</a> and Corollary <a href="#cor.subcritical" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="cor.subcritical">15</a>, $S^{\sharp}_z$ is almost reducible. Since $\Phi$ is Diophantine, by Theorem <a href="#Eli92" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Eli92">12</a>, there exists $B\in C^{\omega}({\mathbb{T}},\mathrm{PSU}(1,1))$ such that $$\label{eq.conjugte1}
[B(\theta+\Phi)]^{-1}S^{{\sharp}}_{z}(\theta)B(\theta)=A,$$ where $A\in{\mathbb{SU}}(1,1)$ is constant. By Theorem <a href="#thm:gapEdgeRd" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:gapEdgeRd">13</a>, $z\in\mathop{\mathrm{rot}}^{-1}(k\Phi/2)$ is unique if and only if $A=\mathbbm 1$.

Fix $\theta\in{\mathbb{T}}$ and assume that $z$ is a collapsed gap of the spectrum of $W^\top_{\lambda_2,\lambda_1,\Phi,\theta}$ with $\lambda_1<\lambda_2.$ Since the cocycle $(\Phi,S^{{\sharp}}_{z})$ is subcritical by Corollary <a href="#cor.subcritical" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="cor.subcritical">15</a>, <a href="#eq.conjugte1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.conjugte1">[eq.conjugte1]</a> boils down to $$^{-1}S^{{\sharp}}_{z}(\theta)B(\theta)=\mathbbm 1$$ and therefore, by <a href="#eq.ConjugatedTransferMatrix" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.ConjugatedTransferMatrix">[eq.ConjugatedTransferMatrix]</a> and <a href="#eq.transposeIter" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.transposeIter">[eq.transposeIter]</a>, $$^{-1}(JRP)^{-1}A_{z}(JRP)B(\theta)=\mathbbm 1.$$ Let $Z(\theta)=JRPB(\theta)$, then $$\label{eq.blochW}
[Z(\theta+\Phi)]^{-1}A_{z}(\theta)Z(\theta)=\mathbbm 1.$$ Let $Z(\theta)=\left[U(\theta),V(\theta)\right]$, where $U,V\in C^{\omega}({\mathbb{T}},{\mathbb{C}}^2)$ are the columns of $Z(\theta)$. It follows from <a href="#eq.blochW" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.blochW">[eq.blochW]</a> that $$\label{eq:UVA}
    \left[U(\theta+\Phi),V(\theta+\Phi)\right]=e^{i0}A_z(\theta)\left[U(\theta),V(\theta)\right],$$ and thus $\{U(\theta+n\Phi)\}_{n\in\mathbb{{\mathbb{Z}}}}$ and $\{V(\theta+n\Phi)\}_{n\in{\mathbb{Z}}}$ are independent Bloch waves of the generalized eigenvalue equation $W^\top_{\lambda_2,\lambda_1,\Phi,\theta}\psi=z\psi$. By Theorem <a href="#thm.reverDual" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm.reverDual">6</a>, these are independent solutions to $W_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\Phi,0}u=zu$.

Fix $\theta\in{\mathbb{T}}$ and assume that $z$ is a collapsed gap of the spectrum of $W^\top_{\lambda_2,\lambda_1,\Phi,\theta}$ with $\lambda_1<\lambda_2.$ Since the cocycle $(\Phi,S^{{\sharp}}_{z})$ is subcritical by Corollary <a href="#cor.subcritical" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="cor.subcritical">15</a>, <a href="#eq.conjugte1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.conjugte1">[eq.conjugte1]</a> boils down to $$^{-1}S^{{\sharp}}_{z}(\theta)B(\theta)=\mathbbm 1$$ and therefore, by <a href="#eq.ConjugatedTransferMatrix" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.ConjugatedTransferMatrix">[eq.ConjugatedTransferMatrix]</a> and <a href="#eq.transposeIter" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.transposeIter">[eq.transposeIter]</a>, $$^{-1}(JRP)^{-1}A_{z}(JRP)B(\theta)=\mathbbm 1.$$ Let $Z(\theta)=JRPB(\theta)$, then $$\label{eq.blochW}
[Z(\theta+\Phi)]^{-1}A_{z}(\theta)Z(\theta)=\mathbbm 1.$$ Let $Z(\theta)=\left[U(\theta),V(\theta)\right]$, where $U,V\in C^{\omega}({\mathbb{T}},{\mathbb{C}}^2)$ are the columns of $Z(\theta)$. It follows from <a href="#eq.blochW" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.blochW">[eq.blochW]</a> that $$\label{eq:UVA}
    \left[U(\theta+\Phi),V(\theta+\Phi)\right]=e^{i0}A_z(\theta)\left[U(\theta),V(\theta)\right],$$ and thus $\{U(\theta+n\Phi)\}_{n\in\mathbb{{\mathbb{Z}}}}$ and $\{V(\theta+n\Phi)\}_{n\in{\mathbb{Z}}}$ are independent Bloch waves of the generalized eigenvalue equation $W^\top_{\lambda_2,\lambda_1,\Phi,\theta}\psi=z\psi$. By Theorem <a href="#thm.reverDual" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm.reverDual">6</a>, these are independent solutions to $W_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\Phi,0}u=zu$.

Moreover, by <a href="#eq.solIter1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.solIter1">[eq.solIter1]</a>, <a href="#eq.ConjugatedTransferMatrix" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.ConjugatedTransferMatrix">[eq.ConjugatedTransferMatrix]</a> and since $P_{2n}$ and $R_{2n}$ are constant for the Verblunsky coefficients of the UAMO specified in <a href="#eq.uamo" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.uamo">[eq.uamo]</a> and <a href="#eq.uamo_rho_gauged" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.uamo_rho_gauged">[eq.uamo_rho_gauged]</a> after gauge transforming, we have $\det A_{n,z}=1$, which implies the constancy of Wronskian. Note that we smuggled a factor $e^{i0}$ into <a href="#eq:UVA" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:UVA">[eq:UVA]</a>: since $0$ is $\Phi$-nonresonant, by Theorem <a href="#thm:AndersonLocal" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:AndersonLocal">4</a> the spectrum of $W_{\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\Phi,0}$ for $\lambda_1<\lambda_2$ and $\Phi\in {\mathrm{DC}}$ is pure point and simple (by constancy of the Wronksian). This contradicts the assumption that $z$ is unique, hence the gap cannot be collapsed. ◻

